hat for every dead on the winning side, there is 3 dead on the loosing side. %0a%3c 4. Casualities%0a%3c     To determine the actual casualities, decide what are the casualities of the winning side. As a default take the average of total army size on both sides and reduce it by two. This is modified by the bloodiness of the battle: for very savage battle reduce only by one, for a formal battle reduce by three. This is the amount of casualities taken by the winning side. The loosing side takes casualities as indicated by the win-loose ratio. The ratio can be translated to unit Size values by taking into account that the mancount triples for every Size-increase, ie. for 1:3 ratio there is +1, for 1:9 there is +2. %0a%3c 5. Other results%0a%3c     Besides casualities, there may be other effects: tactical advantages or special effects. %0a%3c %0a%3c Disasters and critical junctures%0a%3c %0a%3c There are several different kind of natural environmental disasters: an epidemic is the most common, with famine coming close second. Other disasters include a flood, hurricane, earthquake, tornado and drought. The disaster is always assumed to be worst of its kind, so the task should be appropriately difficult. The action determinant is the scope of the society +1, and the task level should be Huge or Epic (-3 or -4). In Elyria game the rounds are 1 year each. To get to the 10%25 for a 5 year period, a ~2%25 per year chance is used, or +-4 on 4DF.%0a%3c %0a%3c Critical junctures are societal/political situations of depression or unrest. An internal critical juncture appears if:%0a%3c %0a%3c     * the ruling agency tyrannizes its people (Power - Authority >= +2)%0a%3c     * consent or power is very low (Consent / Power %3c= Poor)%0a%3c     * tolerance of any humanity is very low (Tolerance %3c= Terrible and Prevalence >= Mediocre)%0a%3c     * severe economic depression (Wealth %3c= Terrible)%0a%3c     * a severe political scandal has occured, like a negotations pledge is broken, an intrigue attempt is failed, ... %0a%3c %0a%3c External critical juncture occures if some society has severily meddled in some other societies actions, or their relations have dropped below Poor (Relations %3c= Terrible). The difficulity of a critical juncture is either Hard or Very hard (-1 or -2).%0a%3c %0a%3c Number of actions%0a%3c %0a%3c The basic number of actions per society is 4. This can be varied, however:%0a%3c %0a%3c    1. extra: -1 to the extra action%0a%3c    2. extras: -1 to both extras, and a -1 to one additional%0a%3c    3. extras: -1 to all extras, and -1 to two additionals%0a%3c    4. extras: all at -1 %0a%3c %0a%3c You can try to remove the action penalty (on a per action basis) by stating that you go cautiously or try something small (relavetive to society scope, of course). The effects won't be that great in the case, though. You can also submit fewer actions, ie. expend extra effort to some actions:%0a%3c %0a%3c    1. less: +1 on one action (also called a "double" action)%0a%3c    2. less: +1 on two actions%0a%3c    3. less: +2 on one action %0a%3c %0a%3c Strategic actions%0a%3c %0a%3c Strategic actions are announced with the keyword 'strategic'. They stretch over a longer period of time, at least two years, at the end of which they are resolved. However, the length of the strategic action need not be declared beforehand. The player just continues the action until he feels that it is ripe time to resolve it. As specific steps, the resolution goes as follows:%0a%3c %0a%3c    1. Player declares strategic action, giving the goal or time estimation.%0a%3c    2. GM determines basic difficulity or gives a time estimation.%0a%3c    3. The player need not adhere to his chosen time limit, however if he uses less time, he'll get penalties:%0a%3c %0a%3c             1/4 of time -> -3%0a%3c             1/2 of time -> -2%0a%3c             3/4 of time -> -1      %0a%3c            %0a%3c %0a%3c       Extra time will grant positive modifiers, for example:%0a%3c %0a%3c             1.5x the time -> +1%0a%3c             2x the time -> +2%0a%3c             3x of time -> +3      %0a%3c            %0a%3c %0a%3c    4. Each round the GM rolls 1DF and tells the player how the project fares. The player may also get modifiers to the strategic action by making appropriately linked normal actions.%0a%3c    5. On the resolve year, decided by the player, 4DF is rolled. This is summed with all previous rolls (and other possible modifiers) and this is multiplied by 4/(N+4) where N is the number of years. %0a%3c %0a%3c Resolution%0a%3c %0a%3c Task resolution in FUDGE is very simple: Result = Skill - Task + Dice%0a%3c %0a%3c In IH context the Skill equals the average of the respective determinants. The task is Normal (0) by default. Both of these can be modified if the situation so warrants. Consult the list below for guidelines on modifiers:%0a%3c %0a%3c     * 0 for unsignificant change in Task/Skill or a small effect from a separately determined random component%0a%3c     * +-1 for a significant change or a normal effect (think about increasing task level from normal to hard)%0a%3c     * +-2 for a big change (task level from normal to very hard) or several (>2) significant changes%0a%3c     * +-3 for an overwhelming change (task level from normal to huge) or several big changes %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c In Elyria the actions will get bonuses for extensive planning/descriptions in the actions description.%0a%3c %0a%3c Technological advancement%0a%3c %0a%3c Depending on the goal the task of making technological advancement is from very hard (-2) to epic (-4) with a tactical action. With strategic action of appropriate length this is lessened to normal in proportion to basic probability:%0a%3c %0a%3c   Very hard (-2) task becomes normal with 1/0.18 = 5 years, %0a%3c   Huge (-3) task becomes normal with 1/0.06 = 17 years%0a%3c   Epic task (-4) task becomes normal with 1/0.01 = 100 years%0a%3c %0a%3c Scope naturally effects the difficulity. Determinants include wealth, resources, scholastics (and possibly magic) prevalence and diversity. The social attitude towards research are governed by scholastics (and/or magic) tolerance.%0a%3c %0a%3c The results of innovation action may be determined as follows: the success value is used as a base point pool. The various effects have point values and the GM picks out a suitable set.%0a%3c %0a%3c  +1    the attempt succeeds!%0a%3c  +1    there is naturally a great demand for it%0a%3c  +1    no need to spread the innovation - just by existing it benefits%0a%3c        everyone%0a%3c  +1    it spreads the customer base of the society%0a%3c  +1    a celebrated artist/crafter who uses the new technique%0a%3c  +1    a genuine technology advance%0a%3c  -1    opponents can easily adapt to it (e.g. in warfare)%0a%3c  -1    it is easy to plagiarize (e.g. a new model/fashion)%0a%3c  -1    it's a great innovation, but it has no real (apparent) use%0a%3c  -1    penalties to spreading attempt (e.g. morally questionable)%0a%3c  -1    setbacks in resources/consent/wealth, shift in power balance %0a%3c  -1    there is a hidden flaw (e.g. it isn't profitable after all%0a%3c        due to large amount of work/equipment/training)%0a
